    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, **Tyler Freeman** (71.80) and **Bryson Stott** (68.43) emerge as our strongest plays, both capitalizing on favorable matchups against sub-optimal starters. **Tyler Freeman** benefits from a massive 14% park factor boost and a soft matchup against Javier; while his stolen base upside is slightly mitigated by a high-caliber opposing catcher, his placement in the #2 hole ensures high-leverage opportunities to boost our R and SB totals. Similarly, **Bryson Stott** finds himself in a prime position, with a 15% SP skill advantage against Mahle and a healthy platoon edge (+13%) that pushes his efficiency well into the \"Strong\" start tier despite a slight park penalty.\n\nWe are navigating a few high-risk matchups, most notably for **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (55.84) and **Daulton Varsho** (52.66), who are both forced to contend with elite arms in Ragans and Ohtani, respectively. These scores are suppressed significantly by the quality of the opposing starters, dragging their efficiency toward our marginal threshold. The most difficult bench decision involved **Matt Chapman** (53.41), who hovered right on the bubble. While he provides a solid floor, the optimizer opted for the higher offensive ceilings offered by **Gavin Sheets** and **Daulton Varsho**, as **Matt Chapman** is hamstrung by a matchup against Nola and an unfavorable defensive environment that limits his overall scoring expectation. As we push for gains in the scarce SB category, we remain cautious regarding the risks posed by elite catchers, which continue to depress the daily projections for **Masyn Winn** and **Bryson Stott**. We will continue to monitor the late-inning pinch-hit potential of **Luis Arraez** should the game script demand a pivot for AVG, though for now, the starting nine remain locked in to optimize for our primary 5x5 objectives.",
